<p>Wisconsin's continental climate presents unique challenges for HVAC systems, with winter temperatures regularly dropping below 0¬∞F and summer peaks reaching the mid-80s with high humidity. The state experiences approximately 7,400 heating degree days annually in southern regions and up to 9,000 in northern areas, making heating efficiency a primary concern. Air conditioning loads are moderate but important, with cooling degree days ranging from 600-900 annually depending on location.</p>

<p>The dramatic seasonal temperature swings require HVAC systems capable of maintaining comfort across a 100¬∞F+ temperature range. Wisconsin homes typically require both robust heating capacity for winter survival and adequate cooling for summer comfort and humidity control. Modern heat pump technology has advanced significantly, with cold-climate air source heat pumps now viable down to -15¬∞F, making them increasingly attractive alternatives to traditional furnace and air conditioner combinations.</p>

<h3>Recommended HVAC Systems</h3>
<p>For Wisconsin's climate, high-efficiency furnaces with AFUE ratings of 90% or higher are recommended for primary heating systems. Gas furnaces remain the most common choice due to Wisconsin's abundant natural gas supply and reliable winter performance. Two-stage or modulating furnaces provide better comfort and efficiency by adjusting output to match heating demands rather than simple on/off operation.</p>

